Hyperosmolar Hyperglycaemic State (HHS) occurs in people with Type 2 diabetes
who experience very high blood glucose levels (often over 40mmol/l). It can
develop over a course of weeks through a combination of illness
Stopping diabetes medication during illness (e.g. Because of swallowing
difficulties or nausea) can contribute, but blood glucose often rises despite
the usual diabetes medication due to the effect of other hormones the body
* disorientation and, in later stages, drowsiness and a gradual loss of consciousness.
Hospital treatment for HHS aims to correct dehydration and bring blood glucose
down to an acceptable level by giving replacement fluid and insulin by an
It does not usually lead to the presence of ketones in the urine, as occurs in
diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), which is why it was previously referred to as
HONK (hyperglycaemic hyperosmolar non-ketotic coma). Ketones develop when the
blood glucose level is high due to lack of insulin which is needed to allow
glucose to enter the cells for energy. Because people with Type 2 diabetes may
still be producing some insulin, ketones may not be created.
* Always take your diabetes medication, even if you feel unwell and can’t eat
* If you monitor your blood glucose, you may need to test more frequently
* Contact your healthcare team if your blood glucose levels remain high (>15mmol/l)
* If you can’t eat, replace meals with snacks and drinks, containing carbohydrate.
